<center><table border=0><tr><td><center><H2><font face=arial>Re: Wait a minute here...</font></H2></center>
<font face=arial size=2><b>Posted By:</b> <A HREF="/cgi-local/whois2.cgi?The RealmWeaver">The RealmWeaver</a><br>
<b>Posted On:</b> 8:24 p.m. 9/2/1999<br>
<b>Subject:</b> Re: Wait a minute here...<p>
<br><center><img src="http://www.everworld.net/pvpquest/images/divider.gif" width=452 height=22 border=0></center><BR><P ALIGN=CENTER><b>In Reply To:</b> <A HREF="http://www.everworld.net/cgi-local/pvp.cgi?read=452" TARGET=_self>Re: Wait a minute here...</A> (Koss)
</STRONG><FONT SIZE=2 color=#FFFFFF FACE=arial>
<P>

<BR>&gt; Its quite easy for monsters to go around killing all the
<BR>&gt; "Do-baders", the problem is that NPCs cant determine
<BR>&gt; what is bad and what is good. There are way too many forms of
<BR>&gt; "bad" and "good".
<P>Would you care to site examples? As far as I'm concerned - there only needs to be one addition. A "criminal" timer. If you initiate combat with another player or steal from that player, you're labeled a "criminal" for a given amount of time based on the severity of your crime and how quickly it has occurred since your last crime. If wandering guards encounter a "criminal" they attack, simple as that and child's play from an AI standpoint. What are all these possibilities you speak of? We're not suggesting the MOBs be able to detect the morality level of the player at the keyboard, only know whether or not he has recently murdered or stolen - this is simple.
<P>&gt; If you make a NPC that
<BR>&gt; goes around killing just bad people, there are going to be
<BR>&gt; countless good people who are going to be killed by these tough
<BR>&gt; NPC's because the NPC is just too dumb to know if the person is
<BR>&gt; good or bad.
<P>&gt; I would much rather be killed by a player killer than killed by
<BR>&gt; a super NPC who kills me for doing something that the NPC
<BR>&gt; considers "bad". While it might be possible for Verant
<BR>&gt; to lay out a complicated list of "good things", and
<BR>&gt; "bad things", this list would have to be HUGE and near
<BR>&gt; impossible for anyone to understand everything on it.
<P>Again, I have no idea what you are talking about. Here's the list:
<P>Bad things:
<P>1.) Attacking another player.
<P>2.) Stealing from another player ( assuming you fail your skill roll and fail ).
<P>3.) Casting a damaging spell on another player ( plague, poison, etc. )
<P>Good things:
<P>1.) Not doing any of the bad things.
<P>That was easy, no? I do not mean to sound condescending, but you are confused. We are not asking for a revolutionary AI system, here, but the changes we propose do not require such a system.
<P>[The RealmWeaver]
<P>dcc5500@rit.edu
<BR>ICQ#: 30795819
<BR>IM: WrldWeaver
</FONT></td></tr></table></P>
